An Accessibility Audit Report of the 2019 Kogi State Gubernatorial elections, conducted by People Living with Disabilities (PWDs) has revealed that 54 percent of sampled polling units in the off-cycle election in the state, were inaccessible to voters with disabilities. The executive director of the Inclusive Friends as well as coordinator of the Access Nigeria Campaign, a non-government organisation that seeks to promote the rights of PWDs, Miss. Grace Jerry, said this at the public launch of an article by her organisation, tagged “ Breaking the Barriers: 2019 Kogi State Polling Unit Accessibility Audit Report”, yesterday, in Abuja. Jerry who revealed that the result is an improvement compared to previous audit report conducted for 2016 Edo and Ondo States elections which showed that 65 percent and 77 percent of sampled polling units were observed to be inaccessible for PWDs respectively, also reiterated that the audit report will provide the pathway that would incrementally advance the inclusion of PWDs in future elections. While calling on President Buhari to establish a National Commission for PWDs, she also urged the National Assembly (NASS) to amend section 42 of the Electoral Act which gives INEC powers to establish polling units by including a precondition that these polling units must be accessible for PWDs. “To promote inclusive budgeting, the NASS should regularly provide funds in the national budget to fund accessible election material and services like Braille Ballot Guides, Accessible Voting Cubicles and Sign Language Interpretation, to enable PWDs to participate effectively in Pre-Election and Election Day Processes”. “The Access Nigeria Campaign also calls on President Muhammadu Buhari to expedite the establishment of the National Commission for PWDs in accordance with part VI, section 31 (1) of the Discrimination Against PWDs (Prohibition) Act 2018 which he signed into law on January 23, 2019, she said”.